segments.text: Looking at anything that had to do with the ocean.
Well, you know, I've been a dabbler most of my life, I guess.
And I guess that's why I'll need to live two or three lifetimes to do all the things that I'd like to do.
But one of the many things that I did as an undergraduate was to work in a fish hatchery.
And I'd kind of had an interest in development, you know, in biological development.
And one could most easily visualize biological development with fish, eggs, and that sort of thing.
And so that was a real interesting area of endeavor for me.

What all this means is that I'd had experience with fish hatchery work, which means that I had experience with fish, which leads to the fact that I thought that there might be some diseases in fish that would be interesting.
And so I saw Leland after the meeting and I said, yeah, I think I might have an idea on that.
He said, he first said,
Well, Don, I believe your plate's full.
He said, you probably ought to get back to EIA.
You've done this pig thing.
Do whatever you want to, but I really don't, he said, I don't see where.
So I said, well, it's something I'm kind of interested in.
So being the kind of person he was, he just let me go home and do it.
So I wrote a project, put together a project.
And then I got to thinking about it.
You know, the veterinary profession has sort of dropped the ball on swine, on the swine industry.
I think this might be
an area that the veterinary profession ought to be involved in.
So then I got to talking it up among some of the other people in some of the other departments.
And I thought it might strengthen the proposal if I got other people in other departments involved in it.
Well, most of them said, yeah, Louis, put my name on there.
That's all right.
I'll do that.
So to kind of make a long story short, I put together a proposal.
that involved all the major departments of the college, and submitted it to the Sea Grant people.
Well, John wore many hats, and he was in charge of the Sea Grant operation.
Now, he may not even remember me personally.
I don't know whether he does or not.
But I put this proposal together and submitted it to him,
And he sent it to the people, you know, the NOAA people, and that was something they really were interested in.
In fact, they got very interested in it and gave it and funded it at a fairly high level.
Now, let's see.
Seems like that was around $250,000 or $300,000 that they funded.
That's a large amount for Sea Grant even today.
Mm-hmm.
Most of those type of things, you get $30,000 to $40,000 and that's about all.
And I think that's about all they do now.
Well, I suggested that aquaculture was really the wave of the future.
And I still think it is.
But unfortunately, it hadn't developed to the extent that I think it could have or should have.
At any rate,
So that was my next thing to get involved in aquatic research.
And let's see.
I kind of had an interest in, well, first of all, Archie and Leland and myself,
thought that a good source of specimens and potential interest would be the Parks and Wildlife Department in Austin.
So they said, well, why don't you call, ask me, why don't you call, call some people in Austin and see if they'd be interested in collaborating with us.
I've forgotten the name of the individual with whom I talked at that time and I said, you know, I was visiting with them on the phone and I said,
We'd like to run with the College of Veterinary Medicine and we're kind of interested in looking into the potential disease problems that fish may have.
And this is the part of the state that is responsible for the state fish hatcheries and so forth.
And the person that I was talking to was, I don't remember his official title, but he was in charge of those fisheries and
And I didn't know it at the time, but they had been kind of under the gun from the legislature as far as problems that were happening in the hatcheries.
But when I suggested that fish may have some diseases, and that may be part of the problems that they're having, boy, he really became very defensive.
And he said, fish don't have diseases.
And I talked with him for a little bit.
I said, you gotta be kidding.
He said, no, we don't have any.
See, the poor guy had apparently been under the gun from his funding sources because of the problems that he was having.
But at any rate, he wasn't wanting to collaborate with us.
He wasn't wanting to uncover any problems with their hatchery systems.
And so we, but we still did have the Sea Grant people and then we got to working real closely with the federal agency in Galveston.
And at that time, they were trying to develop shrimp culture and were having some problems and some of the problems that they were having were due to a particular bacterium, Vibrio.
The name doesn't make much difference, but it's a bacterium.
And also about that time, the college felt like that, and I concurred, felt like that it would be good if we had a veterinarian, a practicing practitioner who had some experience with fish diseases.
And so they did find someone that had had some experience with him and brought him in and gave him a pretty good salary and that sort of thing.
He was an individual that had some, he just wasn't real easy to get along with, with most people.
And I guess that's putting it kind of mildly, including Al Price.
He and Al didn't get along.
He and another guy, Fred Maurer, had come on board at that time, who was real Army research-oriented.
That's M-A-U-R-E-R. That's correct.
And he and Fred had numerous knockdowns.
I mean, they really, this fellow had a lot of problems.
He and, he just,
He was kind of like a rebellious adolescent in many respects.
I won't mention his name because I don't want to incriminate him.
Well, he's dead now, but I think so.
But at any rate, he didn't work out.
And so...
while he was working on, while he was gonna assume the helm on the aquatic stuff, I started looking for other things to do research on.
I was interested in working with fish, but I was also wanting to try to explore other areas.
Well, when he left then, I felt like I had an obligation to move back to the aquatic area, and I did.
And about that time, let's see,
There was, oh, just thinking of the presidential succession, Earl Rutter, Jack Williams, then Vandiver.
Wait, Jarvis.
Yeah, well, there's another story about Jarvis and let's see, Earl Rutter.
Well, anyway, let me tell you this brief story about Earl Rutter.
I had been a graduate student here.
And I had just become appointed on the faculty in the college, and I was walking across the campus one day.
And he came to work early every morning.
He came to work about 7.30 or so.
And I was walking across the campus one day, and he said, Hello, Don, how are you?
That blew me away.
I didn't.
I didn't know why he knew my name, but he apparently knew all of them.
He made it his business to know all the faculty members by first name, and I guess that's true.
What do you think was the perception by the veterinary faculty of Mr. Rutter?
Oh, they held him in high regard.
They held him in very high regard.
And he didn't come over there and walk around much, did he?
No, no, no.
That's what I thought.
No, he didn't.
Now, the story of Highway 6 going both ways, I sat in on that meeting.
I was there at that meeting.
Quite frankly, I kind of agreed with him.
Because there were a lot of people that were expressing dissatisfaction over trivial issues that really didn't need to be, they didn't need to be.
Yeah, I understand the point he was trying to make far more clearly now than I did then.
Yeah.
Because I've been on both sides of that table.
I hear you.
I hear you, yeah.
But to directly answer you, I know you're, you know, I don't want to waste any more of your time than necessary.
No, no, no.
But he was held in high regard.
Right.
But I don't think, I'm not aware of anyone, maybe not even Al Price, I'm not aware, he,
Apparently, Earl wasn't the sort of person that you could just sit down and have coffee with.
Not very easily, no.
Now, what about Jack Williams?
Did you all... Oh, yeah, thought very highly of him.
He was the kind of person that you could...
In fact, well, he was another one that...
I remember shopping in what used to be, you know, Skaggs-Opperson over there.
It's not... At the Circle at Northgate?
Yeah.
And...
I was shopping in there and he again called me by my first name and asked me how the family was and that sort of thing.
I never knew why people at that level go to the trouble of knowing about people at my level at that time.
But anyway, yeah, Jack Williams was held in real high regard.
And I think you'll find that to be a consensus if you ask that same question to any of these other people.
All right, now, it's during his time that George Shelton, Dr. Price retires.
George Shelton becomes the new dean.
Describe anything you recall about the search and the feelings when he came and how he began his task.
Well, there were mixed feelings about him.
I mean, it's sort of like a brotherhood was dissolved.
Because everybody knew each other well.
He had come out of a group of his contemporaries.
That's correct.
In fact, I guess this doesn't speak very well for graduate education at that time, but most of the people that held graduate degrees at that time were on each other's, were directing each other's.
I mean, it was a real close brotherhood type thing.
And really, I don't think, some of it had some substance, but a lot of it didn't have much substance to it.
That's a side issue, and maybe it's not even relevant.
Maybe it's not even important, but there's some quality issues that quality wasn't as good as it could have been.
Did Dean Shelton make any changes?
Yes.
Well, slowly, but he did.
He had a hard time initially.
Well, quite frankly, Leland didn't like him very well.
But he'll never say that and probably I shouldn't be saying that.
But he actually, I think, some people thought he's kind of dull, not too bright really.
I mean, that's what I mean is not too bright.
But he soon came across as an individual that was pretty sly politically.
Let's see, let me add an editorial note here.
Okay.
When the search was nearing its completion, I, as the chairman of the search committee, went in to Dr. Jack Williams, the president, and summarized for him what we had done.
And I told him that we had tried to have a representative of every segment of the veterinary medicine public.
That is, there was a former student and faculty and students and so forth.
And that when each of the interviewees had come to the campus, they had had an interview session with each group, with the vet faculty, with the department heads, with the students, and so forth.
And then that I, as chairman, went back to those groups and got each of them to rank all of the interviewees and had given a point.
They were to rank them in order.
And so I score.

Williams sure there were two people that had were ranked highest and it was all their point score were almost exactly the same and one was George Shelton who was then the associate dean of veterinary medicine at the University of Missouri and the other was a man who had been the dean of veterinary medicine at Ohio State and after a year and a half or two years he and Ohio State had parted company angrily and apparently he could tell told them where they could go and what they could do when they got there
I had been very much attracted by his brilliance.
I thought he was exciting.
And so when I went in to summarize the evaluations for Dr. Williams, I said, now this man from Ohio State will be controversial.
Some of his ideas are not apparently that good, but some are really good and some are exciting.
And that place will be jumping.
There will be something going on all the time.
I mean, it will be.
And some of them may make front pages.
He said, tell me about this other man.
I said, well, Dr. Shelton will be much more quiet, much more reserved.
There won't be any excitement.
There won't be any cataclysmic changes, but things will just get gradually better, I think.
I think he will work well with the public, particularly with the veterinary public and so forth.
Dr. Williams quickly said, I've got enough damn excitement in my life, thanks to the Board of Regents.
And he said, let's go with this man named Shelton.
End of note.
Well, I don't remember...
I don't remember very much about the various people that were interviewing at that time.
Shelton worked out to be fine.
All right, after he got here, how did his deaning relate to what you were trying to do?
See, we were in some turmoil at that time.
Leland Grumbles had stepped down and Charlie Hall had taken over, the Charlie Hall that's in our department.
And Charlie and Leland were very good friends until

Charlie became department head and then they started having problems and part of the mix that was part of the same mix that you know Al Price was having problems at that time so our so the school was in sort of a turmoil and I'm saying things that I probably ought you know I would not
would not want to incriminate Charlie or Leland or Al.
These are just things that happen.
These are just things that happen.
I have the greatest respect for all of those people.
I mean, they're very, people whom I admire and they're very good friends.
Or, you know, in the case of Al, was a very good friend.
But there was a lot of turmoil.
And so, what I'm about to say is,
George came on board, he was there about six months, and Charlie decided he wanted to step down.
Didn't want to be department head anymore.
So they did an extensive department head search.

You may recall, I don't know whether you were here or whether you would have been in the loop with department head searches or not, but they did an extensive department head search, and apparently no one, no one had taken over.

George came to me one day just out of the clear blue and said Don I need somebody to lead this department I said gee I said I haven't had any administrative experience he said well my back's to the wall I really need somebody to help me said if you if you would might said this can be an interim type thing in fact it probably should be I said

Dr. Shelton I really I'm reluctant to do this I don't know I've never I said I've been in the laboratory most of my life and he said well I said Leland and and Charlie both recommended you and I'd sure appreciate it if you'd consider doing it so I so I did I acted in that fashion for I guess a year and a half
Describe what it was like to be the interim department head.
Scary.
Scary to me.
What were the primary worries, concerns?
Well, there were a lot of things that were wrong that I felt like a true department head would need to correct.
And I didn't know how long I was going to be there, and I knew that I was going to have to be moving back to, you know.
So that, I'd be moving back to the, you know, I don't,

mean I'd be moving back to the trenches to use the vernacular and I didn't want to do anything because I had just about everyone I felt everyone was a friend and but but many of them weren't doing what I felt like they should be doing and we had I mean we had problems secretarial problems and you know various types of problems like that and I was really afraid of that situation um
So then I, you know, for about two or three months, I kind of really agonized over those problems.
And it's probably, that's probably the reason why I, you know, I'm not an innate, innately good administrator because of the, because I don't know that I am.
I don't know whether I am or not, but.
What did you find for, of the realities you had to cope with?
Okay, first of all, I had to fire a secretary.
I did that.
I did it and I went to sleep, slept fine.
I had to suggest to an individual, I mean a faculty member, that they probably ought to move along because they're not doing what they need to be doing.
It's in their best career interest to move along because this environment is probably not good for them.
I mean, I had tears.
It was really a tough thing to do, but I said, I'm sorry.
you're not gonna be getting tenure.
And you may as well consider that right now.
And then there was some of the old timers that had been there for some time that I felt like that they oughta be doing something different than what they were doing.
And they didn't like it, but I felt like that they really had to do it.
And in fact, one of them went to Shelton,
And Shelton apparently told him that I was right.
So he backed you?
Yeah, he backed me completely, and that was good.
Were there any pleasant moments, satisfying moments?
Oh, yeah, yeah, sure, sure.
I think, you know, you pass along, you know,

sometimes you receive a gift and you just look for opportunities to I mean sometimes you receive a good thing through the goodness of somebody's actions or thoughts or something and I feel like I had the chance to do that on a couple of occasions the people ultimately left here but they were much I feel like by my giving them a break and you know encouraging them in some way I think they left here

better people than than they would have been and that that was really it felt good um and in terms of hours that the duties god I never realized how much was there's a lot of paperwork maybe more than maybe because I was somewhat compulsive because I really you know I really tried to get everything outlined and really tried to well it's sort of like a
Well, I guess sort of like a new bride or something.
You really want to try to do everything as best you can.
Now, did anybody, while you were department head, pull out the old card about you're not a DVM?
No.
The one individual who I said weren't going to get tenure kind of intimated that.
But no, we really didn't.
All right, and then did you seek the department headship on a permanent basis, or did you go back and say, thank you?
Well, I didn't seek it, but I would have been happy to serve there for a while longer.
They continued, and I suggested that they continue with the search.
And there were two people that were interested in the project,
in the position and I thought they were going to come.
One person, one of the best persons that would have been a very, in my opinion, would have been a very good department head

didn't come and the next best person uh did come and he was worked out to be pretty good too I'm talking about Ian Tizard Ian was Ian Tizard E-A-N no I-A-N I-A-N Tizard T-I-Z-A-R-D T-I-Z-A-R-D yeah he he he was my all right and he was here is he still here yeah he's still on the faculty and he served he served for a number of years actually uh
Let's see, about five years ago, I'm talking about five years ago.
And you went back to the full-time faculty, and what were your tasks then?

Well, the people over in the Research Foundation, when they heard that I had taken the interim, I don't know if you know Jimmy Dodd or not, but he was sort of the person that did a lot of the groundwork for research proposals and so forth.
He said he was disappointed that I went into the administration because he thought that I'd never be able to recover my research.

I would never be able to get, by losing stride, I would never get back to the, and I felt like that, kind of felt like that too, but sort of shortly after I got back, I wrote a project again in the aquaculture area,
one of the USDA competitive grants and got right back in there.
All right so this is now in the about 80?
About 81, 82.
Now let's go back to the campus-wide administration.
You had positive words about Dr. Williams and Jarvis Miller becomes president after him.

you said you had a story to well there's I I don't know you know uh yeah I'm gonna I'm gonna mention it see Jarvis used to be uh uh director of the experiment station for a while and Jarvis and John Calhoun um I got the impression that they didn't have much use for each other well see Calhoun resigned when the day Jarvis was appointed
Okay, I'm not surprised at that.
And then Jarvis replaced him with Mack Prescott as the vice president for academic affairs.
Okay, okay.
Cuz we didn't call it provost then.
You're right, right.
I was in a meeting one time.
The purpose was, see, our program at the vet school was one of the larger programs, at one time, was one of the larger programs in Sea Grant.

and John was in charge of Sea Grant and actually we had more to do with fisheries projects than the Department of Wildlife Fisheries did in Sea Grant and so it also most of the people in the vet school held an experiment halftime experiment station appointment so

Jarvis was kind of looking out for the people in wildlife fisheries and kind of looking out for the people in vet medicine as far as Sea Grant was concerned and John was trying to do the same thing only they had had different perspectives on the way that it should be handled and so the two of them called a meeting a joint meeting that involved
the Sea Grant people, the Sea Grant investigators, you know, me and several of the people out there at that school, and the people in Wildlife History Sciences, and we had a joint meeting.
And, oh gosh, I can't remember all the verbiage that went around, but...
John said something about, well, the vet school ought not to have all this stuff on fish.
That's really the domain of the Wildlife Fishery Science Department.
And Jarvis turned over to me and looked at me and asked me, he said, Dr. Lewis, do you feel that way?
I mean, I was on the spot.
I said, well, I think we just have to let the chips fall where they may.
I think that you know that I'm not a veterinarian, but I think that...
that any matters that have to do with animal health is logically part of the training of the veterinary profession.

And it's time that the veterinary profession, I don't remember my exact words, but the veterinary profession should be encouraged to be involved in health care of fish just like they're involved in health.
Their training leads to that.
Well, I don't know whether that was, I don't know what

what the what impressions were led left as a result of those comments or what but about well six months later I heard that Jarvis is going to be the president and that and and I didn't know for sure I didn't know
I really didn't know what happened to John because someone else took over secret activities at that time.
Yeah.
Oh, well, I don't really know who that was.
Was it Bob Berg?
Worth Nallen?
Worth Nallen, I believe, or Bob Berg was involved in it.
